    <fr:title text="Image finite posets are locally spectral">Image finite posets are locally spectral</fr:title>
    <fr:taxon>Lemma</fr:taxon>
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter><html:p>
  For <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> an <fr:link href="/topl-Q322/" title="Image finite posets" uri="https://charloced.github.io/topl-Q322/" display-uri="topl-Q322" type="local">image finite poset</fr:link> with Alexandroff topology, it is a <fr:link href="/topl-VV9N/" title="Spectral spaces" uri="https://charloced.github.io/topl-VV9N/" display-uri="topl-VV9N" type="local">locally spectral</fr:link> space.
</html:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors /><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>6</fr:month><fr:day>13</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
  <html:p>
    In the Alexandroff topology, opens are exactly upward closed sets. Hence, compact opens are exactly finitely generated, hence finite by being image finite, upsets. They evidently form a basis, and are closed under intersections. 
  </html:p>
  <html:p>
    Hence, it suffices to show it is sober. Suppose now we have an irreducible closed set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C]]></fr:tex>. Consider the following procedure:
    <html:ol><html:li>Pick some <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x_0\in  C]]></fr:tex>;</html:li>
      <html:li>If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\downarrow  x_i \subsetneq  C]]></fr:tex>, then pick <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x_{i+1}\in  C - \downarrow  x_i]]></fr:tex>.</html:li></html:ol>
    If this process never terminate, then we have an infinite strictly increasing chain of elements <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x_0 < x_1 < \cdots ]]></fr:tex>, contradictory to image finiteness of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>. Hence, we must have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C = \downarrow  x_i]]></fr:tex> for some <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i]]></fr:tex>, which implies <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C]]></fr:tex> has the generic point <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x_i]]></fr:tex>.
  </html:p>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter>
